article.headline: LSU's Davis finishes with double-double after shaky start
article.linkText: Dismal Oregon St. shooting opens door for LSU win
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- The atmosphere surrounding
seventh-ranked LSUs non-conference game against McNeese State on
Wednesday was not normal, but the final result was as expected.

Playing on a weekday afternoon just prior to a five-day
Christmas break, the Lady Tigers whipped the Cowgirls 83-28.

"It wasn't hard to play, but it was different," LSU coach
Pokey Chatman said.

Sylvia Fowles and Quianna Chaney combined for 34 points as the
Lady Tigers (12-1) posted their most lopsided victory of the
season.

Fowles led LSU with 20 points, all but two coming in the first
half. Fowles, who grabbed nine rebounds, made all seven of her
field goal attempts. Chaney finished with 14 points, her fourth
consecutive game in double digits.

"Sylvia established herself on the offensive end of the
floor," Chatman said. "Then, it was nice to see Quianna continue
her hot shooting. Overall, I thought it was a good performance
going into the break."

LSU, which extended the nation's longest homecourt winning
streak to 38 games, held the Cowgirls (2-9) to 21 percent shooting
from the field. McNeese committed 29 turnovers which led to 37 Lady
Tigers points.

"LSU has a lot of weapons," McNeese coach Carol Sensley said.
"They are a very well-balanced team that always plays hard. We
have been battling and struggling trying to get people to step
up."

The Lady Tigers played without point guard Erica White, who was
serving a one-game suspension. RaShonta LeBlanc shifted over to
point guard and freshman Allison Hightower replaced White in the
lineup.

"Erica's situation will be evaluated after the Christmas
break," Chatman said. "The suspension was just a coach's
decision. She was just behaving in a way not befitting Lady Tigers
basketball."

Courtnee Hollins was the leading scorer for McNeese with 11
points. Shonice Sprouse, the Cowgirls top scorer, ended with just
three points.

McNeese could not even reach double digits in points during the
first half. The Cowgirls made just three of 21 shots from the field
in the opening 20 minutes. McNeese also committed 15 first-half
turnovers, which led to 17 LSU points.

The nine points scored by the Cowgirls equaled the fewest by a
Lady Tigers opponent in one half. Alabama State scored nine points
in a half during a 65-19 defeat four seasons ago.

LSU put together two substantial runs while building a 38-9
halftime advantage. After 3-pointer by Hollins left McNeese behind
4-3, the Lady Tigers scored ten consecutive points.

Chaney sank a pair of baskets, while Fowles added a field goal
and a foul shot. Chaneys second field goal gave LSU a 14-3 lead
with 12:49 remaining in the first half.

The Lady Tigers then closed the first half with a 13-0 run
following a basket by Joanna Klutarich. Fowles was the key player
during this outburst as she scored nine points. The remaining
points came on field goals by reserves Katie Antony and Marian
Whitfield.

The situation did not improve for McNeese after halftime. It
took the Cowgirls more than four minutes to make their first field
goal of the second half. LSU outscored McNeese 13-2 before Heather
Broussard hit a shot with 15:41 remaining in the game.

McNeeses only points in the first four minutes came on two foul
shots by Hollins. The Cowgirls were guilty of turnovers on five and
their first six second-half possessions. Chaney knocked down a pair
of 3-pointers for LSU during the early second-half run.
